Chris--
 
Certainly the good doctor bad insurance claims investigator (does anybody
out there remember Johnny Dollar on Saturday afternoon radio?!?) is just
silly.  I didn't say that though perhaps (?) Jonathan did.
 
I also think it's been shown (by Brook Thomas and Neil Schmitz and others)
that Walter Michaels is largely a perpetual motion machine driven by
tautology (all literature participates in its culture loop loop loop) but
it's still potentially interesting (to me, anyway) to note, sometimes w a
shock of surprise, how "insurgent" work is often most oddly embroiled in the
social structures it's aggressively rejecting just where it's most exciting.
And I'm persuaded by Bloom, and then in a different way by William James,
that Emerson is already busy doing a lot of what's most
exciting--poetically, intellectually--in Stevens' poetry, and that the
prodigious scholar in Stevens is an exciting trope and not just a fussy one.
And in Emerson, the formulation of a vision of imaginative power that powers
a lot of American poetry--up through Pound and Fenollosa and then wherever
you imagine that lineage to have fructified, to gesture at just one thread
out of many--is part of an argument, early on, in great essays like "The
American Scholar,"  that's agitatedly anti-capitalist.  But if it turns out
that just where Emerson is opposing the powers of the thinker or the poet to
the ways and means of the emerging economy, and just where he's saying the
things that will be so productive for future poetries, he's describing what,
with a small twist, would be just the thing he's opposing--well, that seems
like a good place to focus attention, though stopping with the assertion
that all supposed opposition is just a genteel tradition of liberal
handwringing that does no more than replicate what it bemoans is a sad place
to stop.  Since I don't WORK on Emerson, I mean I'm not gonna write on him,
I'm not sure of just where I'd want to go in this instance.  Quentin
Anderson's analysis in /Making Americans/ is one promising avenue, though
his Rx is too tied up in reveries of the heyday of the New York
Intellectuals to be very convincing.
 
Perelman is an interesting figure to bring up, I think (as Chris did) right
next to Stevens, since so much of a book like /Captive Audience/ takes
something like the inguistic leverage Cavell talks about Thoreau deploying
(in the early parts of /The Senses of Walden/) and shortens the length of
the lever.  That is, the space between current usage and the critical
resonance Bob lets us hear in "our" words is almost non-existent, but not
quite.  This might be mapped onto the conclusion of the Jameson /Pomo/ book.
(btw, that Charles B should so often deploy Cavell's "our" without quotation
marks is, to me, an odd and interesting, and troubling, move.)
 
Chris: since you mention the sort of conjuncture I brought up as akin to the
solipsism of a purely aestheticizing discourse: what's, for you, a happy
counter-instance?  What would be both more productive, and less solipsistic,
to say about Stevens, or Perelman?
 
best,
 
Tenney
