Date:         Sun, 29 Oct 1995 08:47:17 PST
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         Jerry Rothenberg <jrothenb@CARLA.UCSD.EDU>
Subject:      Re: Hypertext & Poetry Possibilities
 
Concerning Jim Rosenberg's digression regarding concrete poets & Black Mountain
poets, etc., let me just say that it doesn't correspond at all to my memory
of all of that.  What I recall is a relative indifference back & forth, with
as much occasional hostility on one side as on the other & several notable
crossovers.  Remember too that most of the active concrete poets -- at the
height of that "movement" -- were European and Latin American, therefore at
a considerable remove from the activities of the New American Poetry.  In
all of my contacts there -- which were extensive -- I didn't pick up
anything of that sort and was much more aware of a kind of Black Mountain
dismissal of the concrete people as superficial or gimmicky or whatever.
The great crossover figure for me was Mac Low but there were others of us
too who found the presence of both of these forces (along with several more)
a matter of the greatest excitement in the 1960s and 70s.  My initial take
on Language Poetry was that it overplayed its connections to the New
American poetry & seemed oblivious to the experiments of concrete and
textsound poets & the promise offered by those.  Tht changed over the years
& all for the better, I think, but the culpability of the Concrete Poets
as such seems much too on-sided a view of the matter.
 
Otherwise, by the way, I think that Rosenberg's discussion of the hypertext
possibilities, etc. is exciting & (for me at least) enlightening.  How it
might be presented in a book as a part of the active poetic present (a
similar problem comes up with sound poetry like, e.g., Chopin's poesie
sonore) is something I'd like to see solved (if that's the right word) in
terms of the big-book project Joris and I are currently engaged with.
 
 
Jerome Rothenberg
jrothenb@carla.ucsd.edu
 
ps. You might note -- if it's an indication of anything -- that in Donald
Allen's updated New American Poetry (with its strong Black Mountain
emphasis) there was not a retrospective sign of anything vaguely approaching
concrete or visual or textsound poetry (among other omissions) -- which
looks to me like at least a mutual indifference.  But obviously concrete
never took hold in North America and if you narrow the field of poetry to
the U.S.A. alone, you're already eliminating (with a very few exceptions) the
genuine innovators & developers of all of that.  Anyway ...
