Date:         Sun, 29 Oct 1995 14:06:26 -0400
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         Kenneth Sherwood <V001PXFU@UBVMS.BITNET>
Organization: University at Buffalo
Subject:      hypertext--media--baseballs
 
Looking for Homer's baseball?  I may want to retract this before it
bounces back on tomorrow morning's digest--but there is no baseball
in Homer; his persistance needs to be accounted for either by the
new equiptment accorded him in, say, Fitzgerald's translation...
or a cultural investment of 'believing in Homer's great baseball.'
 
Why is this anti-sports tone necessary?  It seems that as soon as
we start talking about a 'value' or 'quality' to a given poetry
which escapes the ravages of time or the transformations of its
media, we've dematerialized it completely.
 
Put pragmatically--what do we get by talking about the poem apart
from its versions: manuscript, drafts, first magazine publication,
small-press book version, electronic reprint, etc.?
 
Let's be blunt and/or reductive.
 
You can't have your baseball and eat it too!  Either 'good poetry
is platform independent' (baseball view) or 'there is no such
thing as the words themselves' (Charles A.)
 
The other problem I sense in talking about the somehow pure poetry
that 'comes through' *despite*... is that it seems necessarily
bound up with the recriminant notion that those poetries which
haven't made-the-cut must have lacked the 'pure poetry' that
would have shined through.
 
ks
