Date:         Sun, 29 Oct 1995 13:48:56 -0600
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         Charles Alexander <chax@MTN.ORG>
Subject:      visual poets
 
Jim Rosenberg's comments on the inflexibility of concrete poets, and that
such inflexibility and intolerance set the art of poetry back 20 years, just
seems wrong to me. Admittedly I was not terribly aware of visual poetry or
other innovative poetries until the mid-1970's, but from what I know it
seems that there was at least as much intolerance toward visual poetry as
there was intolerance coming from visual poetry. And when I think of poets
like Karl Young, bpNichol, Jackson Mac Low, Karl Kempton, Jonathan Brannen,
and others, I don't see much intolerance at all; rather, I see poets
practicing visual poetry among various strategies to expand the whole art. I
think if we ignore the visual poetry of these and others, we miss an
important part of late 20th Century poetry.
 
For a different view, a belief that poets engaged in various schools did NOT
set back the art 20 years, rather helped it continue forward, I quote from
Karl Young's essay, "Notation and the Art of Reading," in Open Letter vol.
5, no. 7, from the late 1970's, which will be part of his forthcoming book
of collected essays, Only As Painted Images Have We Come To Be In This
Place, which Chax Press will publish in 1996.
 
"At present there are at least twenty major schools of poetry functioning in
North America, each with dozens of subgenres. No group dominates, so poets
at the present time enjoy more freedom than they ever have in the past.
Members of some schools can be dogmatic and exclusionist, and members of one
clique can become extremely bellicose toward another coterie, but few, if
any, can limit their interests and contacts to members of their own groups.
Hence poets belonging to one clan can be influenced by members of another --
in fact, many poets switch allegiances during their careers, and many
function in several schools at once. The cross-fertilization among these
groups produces all sorts of hybrids, sometimes showing a great deal of what
biologists call hybrid vigor. We should note that what poets work against is
often as important as what they work with, and even antagonisms can be
productive. As well as producing hybrid vigor, interaction among schools
seems always to exert an influence on notation, keeping it from becoming
rigid or consistent, and opening up new possibilities."
 
While I admire the leaps into new worlds of visual possibilities of Jim
Rosenberg's work, I don't think it needs to come with a putdown of earlier
visual poetry, which, I think, has helped us rather than hindered us.
 
charles alexander
=========================================================================
Date:         Sun, 29 Oct 1995 13:59:28 -0600
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         Joe Amato <amato@CHARLIE.ACC.IIT.EDU>
Subject:      Re: Hypertext & Poetry Possibilities
 
jerry, first off let me say (which i've posted backchannel to pierre) that
your and pierre's newly released anthology is an incredible achievement...
what i find intriguing is that you've managed in many ways to offer an
example of how to constructively alter the activity of anthologizing *even
as* jed's book emerges, a book that critiques past such efforts... striking
synchronicity here, methinks...
 
anyway, to cut to the chase:  i don't see how you'll manage a compilation
of electronic text in other than electronic form, just don't see it...
seems to me that there is surely a similar problem in translating various
print objects of art into a simpler, paper-bound medium... but the
electronic distinction is complicated not only by some fundamental changes
in reading e/affects (depending in part on one's, uhm, sensitivities), but
by, for example, the various platforms for which the text in question has
been designed/initially composed... to wit:  is reading the windows version
of _afternoon_ equivalent to reading the mac version?... is there any
subtle (or significant) difference here intrinsic to platform/front end, or
is this difference more constructively pursued as a function of differences
twixt mac/windows users/readers, which latter would imply perhaps a
slightly altered theory of reception?...
 
we tend not to talk about how we thumb through a given print manuscript (if
indeed we thumb through it!) but hitting the keyboard and clicking a mouse
are different activities (different from each other, that is), and
electronic texts can foreground this difference, too...
 
some tough conundrums here, and i'm sure i'm overlooking lots... but i'd
stick at least with the assertion that an anthology of (electronic!)
hypertext must be electronic...
 
joe
