Date:         Mon, 30 Oct 1995 01:26:32 GMT
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         Tom Beard <beard@MET.CO.NZ>
Subject:      Re: Where's the Hypertext in this Thread?
 
Loss gave an interesting summary of the hypertext (ht) poetry thread. I like
the healthy skepticism that he displays  - "most hypertext writing is awful!" -
and much of the most interesting writings on ht writing that I've seen on the
web (such as the "Search for some ht literature" (I've forgotten the author &
URL) and the article in FEED at http://www.emedia.net/feed/) has also been
skeptical. I know that I came towards ht with great enthusiasm, and I'm glad
that that has become tempered with some realism. Since then, I've written a
poem that _demanded_ a hypertext presentation, but I always make sure tham I'm
not writing (hype)rtext for its own sake.
 
The poem of mine that Eryque mentioned (thanks Eryque!) was originally written
on paper, but the structure became three dimensional and it was soon evident
that any paper version would "flatten" the poem and privilege certain
directions of reading over others. As it appears on the web (at
http://metcon.met.co.nz/nwfc/beard/www/notes27.html) each lexia/section/poemlet
allows the reader to move in one of six different directions, corresponding to
the six faces of a cube. My intention was for readers to construct their own
readings by reading/slicing/browsing/surfing through this 3D poem, and that
they should email me their readings to me so that I could include them on my
web pages along with the poem. This will-to-interaction faltered, however,
since no-one has sent me a reading yet.
 
The point of this is that this was a poem that did not work on paper, but did
in ht. Maybe I could have constructed something out of perpex or transparent
paper, but I have no space in which to exhibit such a work, and besides, I'm
happier writing HTML than doing manual labour. Perhaps there are some
interesting uses for ht-like structures in conceptual art or sculpture - I
dream of a vast, Hampton Court-style maze, with words embedded within the
living walls. It would be fascinating to track the paths that visitors/readers
take through this maze - perhaps the young would end up in a different part of
the maze to the old; or males and females would tend to take different tracks;
or those who have witnessed a parent die head straight towards the centre,
while people for whom English is a second language find the exit with great
rapidity, and those in unrequited love mill round and around in slowly-
diminishing circles.
 
Going back to why I agree with Loss over most ht-lit being awful, I must
qualify this by saying that I've only really read text-only works on the web: I
haven't tried anything based in Hypercard, and most of the interesting work by
people like Jim Rosenberg & Eduardo Kac won't talk to my little VT-320. Also,
until recently most ht-lit on the web was by people who were programmers first
and writers second, and this showed. I have no doubt, however, that ht shows
_great_ potential for experimental multi-linear narratives. I'm not sure
whether poetry will have as great a potential for ht experimentation, for
reasons that I will try to explain.
 
For a start, most contemporary poetry has no narrative, or at least not in the
linear sense of conventional fiction, so there is no expectation of story-line
to be subverted. There are exceptions, such as epic poetry or stories in verse,
but in language-centred writing as well as in much lyric poetry, we cannot
allow the reader to choose "what happens next", since there is no "next".
 
We could write poems in which words are highlighted, and clicking these words
will take us to different parts of the poem. This is "associative" ht, as
opposed to "plot-based" ht, and it is an interesting possibility. But this is
how I tend to read most poetry anyway, and I've argued
(http://metcon.met.co.nz/nwfc/beard/www/sargeson_ladder.html) that _all_ text
can be read as hypertext in this sense. Even a relatively conventional text can
be read in this way, with words sending the mind racing down links of meaning
and sound, both within the poem and with "pointers" to other texts. This is
truly non-linear reading, as opposed to the "multilinear" reading that someone
so rightly pointed out was the true characteristic of ht. At least with HTML-
style ht, a reader follows one link at a time, whereas reading a poem on the
page can generate a ghostly web of links, existing simultaneously and at
different levels of consciousness, across the poem. It sounds like Jim R's
approach, with superimposed words, may be an incarnation of this idea, and I
wish I had the hardware to view it.
 
Perhaps the most promising creative uses of hypertext will not be in poetry, or
fiction, or criticism; but in modes that have not previously existed. Some of
my favourite web examples of this are OutThere(TM) at
http://www.umich.edu/~rmutt/OT/ (a hypertext non-glossary of Dada, Surrealism
etc; a satirical "Form without Function"; and the homepages of Procrustus Corp,
"brokers of fine intellectual property", sprinkled with extensions to HTML such
as <TASTEFUL> and <HYPNOTIZE>), The E-Ville Dialogs at
http://www.itp.tsoa.nyu.edu/~shana/Dialogues/contents.html (the reader
eavesdrops on philosphical discussions among the diners at a Greenaway-esque
restaurant, trying to talk to the Head Chef, Heraclitus - the overall feel is
somwhere between Kafka and _The Prisoner_) and the Giovanni Bottesini project
at http://www.webcom.com/~redwards/gbmain.html (a mock-historical archive which
makes fine use of layered possibilities - Bottesini has 7 reported dying
sayings, each of which leads the reader on a different track - and reminds me
of Umberto Eco with its conspiracy theories and pseudo-scholarship).
 
Hypertext could also allow for some new forms of critique, with a critic adding
links to a work to make explicit some linkages that were hidden in a linear
text, or creating a hyper-detournement by weaving ht-links between several
diverse texts. It also gives the editors of electronic journals the opportunity
to add both internal and external links to their publications, thereby
expanding the works. Of course, the individual authors should have some veto on
this - I wouldn't like my poems to sprout blue underlined links without my
approval - but there's merit in having a poem that quotes John Cage and alludes
to _The Piano_ accompanied by a subtle selection of links to a John Cage home
page and the Internet Movie Archive's entry on _The Piano_. The Web itself is
the greatest hypertext poem yet written.
 
 
 
        Tom Beard
 
______________________________________________________________________________
I/am a background/process, shrunk to an icon.   | Tom Beard
I am/a dark place.                              | beard@metdp1.met.co.nz
I am less/than the sum of my parts...           | Auckland, New Zealand
I am necessary/but not sufficient,              | http://metcon.met.co.nz/
and I shall teach the stars to fall             |  nwfc/beard/www/hallway.html
