Date:         Mon, 30 Oct 1995 00:39:53 -0400
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         Kenneth Sherwood <V001PXFU@UBVMS.BITNET>
Organization: University at Buffalo
Subject:      return to the tinkering
 
Loss' post calls for a thorough response; I'm afraid I'll just tinker away
at it.  Fact of the Net's dark origins granted--this may be all the more
reason to invoke the playful, insisting that we do toy around, and
that toying is meaningful.
 
Which reminds me of the discussions on 'experimental' some months ago.
I find a value in insisting that one 'toys' around or 'experiments'
because I don't look for poems that act as proof-texts of some
prior seriousness--itself potentially dangerous, no?
 
On a different note, it does seem that one of the elements absent
from the hypertext wing of this discussion is the way that, online
atleast, it involves more than non-linear or interactive writing.
These are (as someone, Tom Beard?) mentioned, attributes of
particular interest to writers of narrative.
 
Increasingly I grow interested in using the multi-media aspect of
electronic writing.  The ability to create and distribute visual
and sound poetry, 'intermedia' (in Dick Higgins' term) compells
my recent writing more than those formal features most typically
associated with hypertext.
 
In this sense, I'd want not only to blur the boundary between
computer generated writing and hypertext (non-sequential writing)
but also that between writer and programmer.  The word has had little
time encrust itself with romantic resonance, but 'programmer'
might be another word for the work Charles Alexander and others
do with the letter press book!
 
Ken S.
