Date:         Mon, 30 Oct 1995 09:27:50 EST
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         "H. T. KIRBY-SMITH" <KIRBYS@FAGAN.UNCG.EDU>
Organization: University of NC at Greensboro
Subject:      Visual Poetry
 
Visual poetry goes way back--to Alexandria in ancient times, and poets
such as Simias who did shaped poems. Then with printing in the
Renaissance the typographical arrangement could involve all sorts of
degrees of originality. I think the early-twentieth-century emphasis
(in the poetry of H. D. and Pound, the criticism of Hulme, poetry of
Williams, cummings, etc) was in part a reaction against those
late-nineteenth-century volumes jammed margin to margin with Idyls of
the King or dramatic monologues.
 
May Swenson is certainly the best visual poet of the second half of
this century--because her poems are also auditory, and because the
visual effect is arranged rather than deranged.
 
Visual poetry seems to coincide with other kinds of revolution or
experimentation--and is scorned by prosodic conservatives, who become
uncomfortable in their scorn when reminded of George Herbert.
 
 
 
Tom Kirby-Smith
English Department
UNC-Greensboro
Greensboro NC  27412
