Date:         Mon, 30 Oct 1995 08:58:46 -0600
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         Joe Amato <amato@CHARLIE.ACC.IIT.EDU>
Subject:      Re: Where's the Hypertext in this Thread?
 
a friendly addendum to tom beard's fine post:
 
tom, i would only say, as i've been saying for a good while now, that the
fact that hypertext doesn't violate the episodic, linear structure of
narrative when it comes to much contemporary poetry is *precisely* the
reason i find it of great significance to what poets can do with same (and,
as in the case of a few folks on this list, *are* doing)... perhaps one
loses the sort of inherent contrapuntal texture that transgression of
narrative-episodic form provides, but what takes its place, depending on
what's actually writ(-composed), is the possibility of rather startling
associative leaps unencumbered by 'plot' as such... (my own preference is
in fact for an anti/metaphysics of place, but this is a whole 'nother
matter)...
 
in general, i think the concept of hybridity (informed perhaps by recent
a-a and postcolonial critical work on same) is a useful way to begin to
rethink the sorts of aesthetic experiences you suggest in various of the
web sites you mention (and thanks for that list, too!)...
 
all best//
 
joe
=========================================================================
Date:         Mon, 30 Oct 1995 15:14:39 +0000
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         John Cayley <cayley@SHADOOF.DEMON.CO.UK>
Subject:      Re: Hypertext & Poetry & Tinkertools & Baseball
 
[I meant to make these short, oh well...]
 
Ken Sherwood:
 
>Calling various forms of computer-writing tinkertoy technology is
>absolutely right, since these forms WILL become outmoded because of
>the role this tech plays apart from poetry.  The "BOOK", itself a
>technology which has changed (hand scripted to letterpress to
>desktop lazerjet) does not tend to outmode itself.
 
Nope, /pace/ all the well-meaning and light-hearted suggestions that it's
good for us to 'go back to' using toys for a while to regain some sort of
'primitive' or 'childlike' naivety in relation to our art (I love to play,
although *not* with computers), I just can't let 'tinkertoy' slip through
as potentially useful characterization of 'programmed machines as
presentors/generators of (some) poetic writing'.
 
Especially, not for the reason that what we use now will (inevitably) be
outmoded tomorrow. The technology of the book has evolved, and *many* book
technologies have been outmoded. The Chinese classics were written on
(amongst other things) strips of bamboo bound together with string
(producing, btw, some interesting quasi-aleatory ethical philosophy when
early editions were dug up with the strings rotted away), they were also
carved on stones (some argue this was *after* the aforementioned
quais-alearoy transformations) which still stand in a 'forest of Stones' in
Xi'an -- multilithic, difficult to use, but not outmoded (you can still
take rubbings).
 
But enough of this playing around, the reason the question of obsolescence
is obsolete is because of the computer-based medium we're using now. It's a
mistake to consider 'some one type of computer running some one piece of
software' as a soon-to-be-abandoned toy, because now all of these systems
are linking themselves together and it won't be long before most (local)
computer-based activity is transparent to the network, regardless of
platform/software etc.
 
My conclusion: nothing of significance (I mean the stinging together of
beautiful/good language, the design and creation of new cyber/hypertextal
forms and systems of text regeneration) that you are doing now with your
computer will be 'outmoded'. You will, sooner rather than later, be able to
make it accessible to others.
 
---
 
Jim Rosenberg:
 
>There's one thing that has to be said here and SAID LOUDLY:  I hope no one
>comes away from this discussion thinking that those of us doing experiments
>with various computer media are trying to hype these media as in any way
>"superior" to the traditional ones.
 
I wanted to concur whole-heartedly these remarks of Jim's.
 
---
 
Jim Rosenberg:
 
>How does one *program* time?  There are some very difficult questions here.
>(I hope John will jump in on this, since he's done the most interesting work
>I've seen with programming time in computer poetry.)  One thing I like to say
>to myself all the time is that:
>
>Syllable Time is not equal to Real Time
 
Programming time: What it seems to me that a poet/+programmer *can* do is
allow a reader to experience a poet's syllable time. Perhaps this also
happens when you simply listen to a recording of a poet performing her
work. But I've always be particularly interested in silent reading, and the
screen, potentially, allows us to experience a rendition of a 'scored'
syllable time in the silent reading of a poem.
 
That said, I mentioned before that I had written a HyperCard stack that
allows you to 'score' poems in this way. Jim wrote about his 'tape loop'
experiment and his surprise at the illusion of simultaneity that the
dominance of stress over musical attack produced. In trying to make the
'scoring' stack I was (and still am) amazed at the fine control required to
'score' words and phrases in a manner that matches my inner ear. HyperCard
(with my current hardware) really isn't up to it. (Ah ha! they all cry -- a
tinkertool...) E.g. I make words appear letter by letter (as if scrolling
rightwards) and allow the speed at which this is done to be adjusted. But
to represent stress properly, you would probably have to have variable
speeds of letter display *within* the presentation of single words (v.
difficult and v. time consuming -- but I'll work on it). However, such
super-sensitivity apart, if you got the time/pause relationships right
(over one screen's worth of text) then the fragment suddenly seems to
click, to work for the inner ear -- ?? like Jim's tape loop phenomenon.
 
[Programming an other time: _The Speaking Clock_ addresses the question of
names for time; the suggestion that a clock should give a different name to
every moment, since every moment of *real* time is different.]
 
---
 
Ken Sherwood:
 
>You can't have your baseball and eat it too!  Either 'good poetry
>is platform independent' (baseball view) or 'there is no such
>thing as the words themselves' (Charles A.)
>
>The other problem I sense in talking about the somehow pure poetry
>that 'comes through' *despite*... is that it seems necessarily
>bound up with the recriminant notion that those poetries which
>haven't made-the-cut must have lacked the 'pure poetry' that
>would have shined through.
 
I really enjoyed and went with this post, but ...
 
I think you *can* have and eat your baseball.* I've heard, from colleagues
who've been there, that you can buy live baseballs in certain markets in
south China and that there are no local taboos against killing and eating
them. So, if we can translate Homer into Chinese, we should be able have,
hold and eat our baseballs in cyberspace. (Also, isn't there a very good
Japanese pitcher doing well in the major leagues? With a really
extraordinary action?? Pl. excuse UKanian ignorance.)
 
best, John
 
* Cf. the unceasing discussions of the problem of translation.
 
