Date:         Mon, 30 Oct 1995 10:22:20 -0600
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         Joe Amato <amato@CHARLIE.ACC.IIT.EDU>
Subject:      Re: Hypertext & Poetry & Tinkertools & Baseball
 
well i'm just really mouthy lately, is all...
 
john's _the speaking clock_ is (again my spockish declaration of late)
fascinating... one of the beauties of this medium is that john was able to
email me his work, from london, within twenty-four hours of my request...
and i had it up and running in about two minutes...
 
mind you, he won't receive my check for mebbe five-seven days, airmail...
 
(it's on its way, john, thanks again!              (((does this guy have
faith in me, or what?...
 
anyway:
 
i think this discussion of ht and electronic form suggests, not so
surprisingly, a conjuncture (a helpful one) in the arts:  that moment when
art---understood by its various communities in terms of its various
practices---finds itself once again (a historical assertion) implicated in
its various technologies AS SUCH... and with a bit of luck, i hope,
technology begins itself to show signs of this, uhm, interfacing...
 
hence we're at the intersection of multiple discourses... hence i want to
introduce the term 'instrumentalist' here (in line with certain theorists
of technology) to indicate that a view toward technology as a tool, as
something we have control over, is generally used to argue in fact that
technology only reinforces dominant, status quo realities... b/c in this
view, technology is a tool (as my students here at the technical institute
tend always to gloss it) "nothing more and nothing less"... hence the
question posed by audre lorde, to wit, how to use the 'master's tools' to
rebuild the 'master's house,' becomes a difficult question indeed...
 
there are other ways of thinking about tools (where's don byrd?), but what
i offer in this latter is the more restrictive sense of the word...
 
now among the various other views of technology, there is the view afforded by
folks like (and for) foucault (say that five times quickly) that technology
is in fact NOT a tool... that it is a far more epistemic construct, and
that we don't exactly 'use' it to produce a desired end product... we
don't, that is, 'control' it---in fact quite the opposite... hence we end
up with the more dire discourses on technology, and the the more luddite
responses to same...
 
in these views, as i've articulated them, the possibility of bringing about
constructive change through technological practice is complicated by either
(1) difficulty in transcending the after-the-significant-fact, make it
OLD/'fix it' role assigned to tools or (2) inability to control a
totalizing (not to say totalitarian) set of practices marked by their
self-replication in capitalist commodity culture...
 
i'm pointing to these two views of technology to suggest a third view (and
fourth, etc):  that if techology is from one pov a tool (yes, it can pretty
much reduce to this, depending on how one construes context) and if
technology is from another pov a set of cultural practices (yes, it can be
this in macro terms, depending again on on how one construes context), then
methinks there is certainly room in this continuum to consider ALL
technologies both as things AND as (social) events (maria damon may want to
jump in here with her notion of the 'margin')...
 
things would include toys, screwdrivers, human beings, hypertexts,
baseballs and global information and control systems...
 
events would include heightened awareness, mindwashing, human beings,
tripping (both senses), striking out and FUN...
 
the instrumentalist concept *tends toward* things (as means to ends), the
epistemic concept *tends toward* events (as mutually contingent
'shapeshifting' processes)... but there are no hard & fast boundaries here,
save to the extent one is attached to one's categories...
 
just some non-inklings, all a bit sloppy and unpolished, high in fiber, and
mebbe not too difficult to digest...
 
joe
