Date:         Mon, 30 Oct 1995 13:27:28 -0600
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         Charles Alexander <chax@MTN.ORG>
Subject:      Re: Visual Poetry
 
>May Swenson is certainly the best visual poet of the second half of
>this century--because her poems are also auditory, and because the
>visual effect is arranged rather than deranged.
 
>Tom Kirby-Smith
 
 
To each her or his own. I don't know about "best visual poet," but I think I
would choose any of the trio of bpNichol, Karl Young, or Karl Kempton. And
this is limiting myself to North America, where in some ways visual poetry
is under-represented, or at least under-recognized. But I find the
explosiveness and sheer inventiveness of Nichol and Young amazing in their
sweep of possibilities. And I find the subtle patterns of Karl Kempton,
based on sources which range from patterns of plankton on the shore to Hopi
and other tribal weavings, to be rich and deep in a way which moves me more
than Swenson's work. Not that there's anything wrong with her work, which is
an important body of work.
 
I also think there are a number of important book artists who should be seen
as visual poets in a kind of Blakean tradition; these would include Susan
King, Patricia Scobey, Nancy Leavitt, and others.
 
all best,
charles alexander
