On Sat, 28 Oct 1995, Charles Alexander wrote:
 
Are you asking these questions because you're about to launch a reading series?
 
Charles--yes. Thanks for your response (and thanks, Ron). Anybody else
have ideas how to hold readings that are a) pleasant b) productive c)
surprising? Any successful hosts (don't be bashful!) who would
like to share their secrets for inviting readers (and please don't point to
the black box, taste!)? Mark Wallace bravely queried members of the list
whether they'd be interested in reading... St. Marks has a "two-year
rule" (can't have a solo reading two years in a row)... what are the
rules elsewhere, such as SPD? Are there people you've wished would read
but just never do? Are there people you wish just wouldn't read
(did you know that the expression "backchannelling" comes from the noises
and movements a listener makes to acknowledge that they've been
listening?)? Is a query like this ironically more likely to keep people
from discussing a troublesome issue than to provoke change?
 
Your fan,
Jordan
