Subject:      Re: & Ralph Waldo
 
   Dear Ed---
   Could you please elaborate, or support your argument (gosh, i feel
   like i'm grading a student paper) about "different poetries" being
   "different economies"---Do you mean "psychic economies" and if so
   how is that NOT a trope? If you mean the COST of books, or the LABOUR
   involved in reading a certain poet, is there a way to determine what
   is the MOST COST-EFFECTIVE poetry? Hmmmm--the kind of poetry that has
   5 words per page is more "taxing" than maximialism? The kind of poetry
   that works good on a first reading but not as much on subsequent ones
   is certainly a ripoff? (This is all very vague). If some poetry DEMANDS
   more from the reader than others (how do you define demand?), is it
   possible it doesn't DRAIN the reader but actually stirs the reader
   to an activity s/he wouldn't otherwise.
   Please, Ed, tell me more--I am quite open to this---
   But I also am skeptical about the validity of what seems to me to be
   a kind of quantification here--It's like sleep.
   Why is it, for instance, that sometimes I am MORE tired when I
   have just woken from a 12 hour sleep than i am when I have woken from
   a 3 hour nap? (I don't expect you to answer that....) Chris S.
