Date:         Mon, 30 Oct 1995 21:30:13 -0500
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         James Sherry <jsherry@PANIX.COM>
Subject:      Re: Evaluation
Comments: To: w.curnow@auckland.ac.nz
In-Reply-To:  <22E1731736A@engnov1.auckland.ac.nz>
 
I suspect that value judgements "are" as you say a subterfuge, a conspiracy
game, designed to establish one's value system as the first system to be
consulted in the event of any value judgement. It is implemented is
through substitution of first person plural in discussing
issues that are only valid in the first person singular. It can also
be accomplished, although less effectively with the Royal WE. Shifters as
McCaffery points out are the arbiters of value. The language game that is
played out here is an attempt to establish a universal context for a
particular context. There is a strong psychological component too.
 
And we can't help it. It is simply a matter of asserting ourselves. I am
just astonished how little else there is in our exchanges. When I was
first moving in a public poetry world, days were spent, days, listing our
pantheons of poets, as we got older we substituted books by poets, then we
substituted poems, then contracts, then diseases. These lists are too
evaluative. What I wanted to have accomplished is substitution of an
analysis for a value judgement, but the psychology of the poet is too
fragile in a weak culture to let writers be free of the need to
continually have their values reaffirmed.
 
I don't think there is any way to stop it short of addressing issues and
that presents its own problems. Even as I type I'm sure I'm engaged in
a form of the same. Let us look like we're doing the rightthing by doing
the wrong thing. Let us cut the budget.
 
James
