on this subject; apologies in advance if it looks like I'm ignoring somebody.]
 
me:
> [I'm gonna get myself in trouble for this]
 
Yup.
 
Jerry Rothenberg:
> Concerning Jim Rosenberg's digression regarding concrete poets & Black Mountain
> poets, etc., let me just say that it doesn't correspond at all to my memory
> of all of that.  What I recall is a relative indifference back & forth, with
> as much occasional hostility on one side as on the other & several notable
> crossovers.
[...]
> the culpability of the Concrete Poets
> as such seems much too on-sided a view of the matter.
 
I'll stand corrected on this, but my basic point remains:  whoever was
responsible, real *dialogue* in poetics between visual poetics and other
forms -- sound too, for that matter -- has been woefully insufficient, and we
must do what we can to increase it.
 
Charles Alexander:
> While I admire the leaps into new worlds of visual possibilities of Jim
> Rosenberg's work, I don't think it needs to come with a putdown of earlier
> visual poetry, which, I think, has helped us rather than hindered us.
 
Oh dear.  Charles, you misunderstood me *COMPLETELY*.  There was no putdown
intended against visual poetry -- the exact opposite.  What I am speaking
against is exactly the lack of interchange.  It is from a belief in the
*value* such a dialogue would have that I bemoan its absence.
 
Yes, there have been many "crossover" figures, as both Jerry and Charles
point out.  But in our *discourse* I find precious little attention to this
cross-fertilization.  If hypertext folk end up talking only to other hypertext
folk it will be a sad sad day.
 
--
