Joe Amato,
 
While I agree with your attempts to define "technology" as both variously
instrumentalist and epistemic, I have a problem that arises from such an
attempt--which is, that if we broaden "technology" too much then the term
becomes watered down and useless.  For instance, I am very much taken
with my colleague (by the way, he is the editor of the new Eco-Journal
TERRA NOVA, which prints poetry and all other manner of beast, and he can
be contacted at NJIT, Newark, NJ 07102 or email him at:
rothenberg@admin.njit.edu) and his ideas especially as they are expressed
in his recent book HAND'S END: TECHNOLOGY AND THE LIMITS OF NATURE, but
in the book he argues that language itself is a technology--whereas, like
Ong or Bolter I guess, I would draw the line at writing.
 
But I know what you mean. . . .
 
 
Burt
