one economy to another) there is a shift from the noun to the verb, that
obsession among so many now, that in american literature emerges so strongly
with emerson. olson, disliking emerson, found older roots in heraclitus.
the essential in this, as in (to take the extreme) laissez faire economics,
is change; the man said, "What does not change / is the will to change," but
that really implies an unchanging "i." in fact the only thing that doesn't
change is change. (indeed you buy something and get change.) the difference
between, say, the poetics of the era of augustus, say, and whitman is linked
to different economies. so, too, wallace and ezra. that does not mean that
poetry is political, but that there are common roots. there is every reason
to argue against althusser, but one could draw on his definition of ideology
here--that which cannot be resisted. and that, in the realm of insurance
(what value do you give your house/life/job) and wallace's supreme fiction,
is essentially (sorry, but that really is the word) alchemical. -ed
