Date:         Tue, 31 Oct 1995 17:39:59 -0800
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         Steve Carll <sjcarll@SLIP.NET>
Subject:      Re: readings desiderata
 
Jordan:
 
I personally like readings which break out of the "reader-break-reader"
format.  A few years back I saw John McNally and Darin DeStefano read at
Small Press Traffic, and they both went up to the front and traded poems
back and forth for an hour or so, ending with a two-voice reading of Kenward
Elmslie's "Girl Machine."  It was brilliant.  Recently I read with Anselm
Berrigan and John M., and we each read solo for ten minutes apiece, then
read together for a half-hour.  Another format I've used is to alternate
readers with musical acts.  Clark Coolidge and David and Tina Meltzer did us
one better, though, by combining these approaches.  David and Clark would
each read, then they'd break out the drums and guitar and back Tina, then
one would solo over the other reading, then they'd trade poems to and fro.
That was really lively.
 
Not that the "regular" way isn't fine, but to vary that routine reinvests it
with an energy that sometimes flags if things get too "samey."
 
One of the tricks to booking a series (although this may depend on the
series) that might not be too obvious is not to overbook.  If you leave some
space in your schedule then you'll have a night for (your favorite poet's
name here) to read when she tells you, "Hey, I'll be in town in 6 weeks.
Anything going on?"  Although you want to balance this with the desire not
to always be finalizing dates at the last possible minute, which makes
getting the word out to your audience more difficult.
 
Steve
=========================================================================
Date:         Tue, 31 Oct 1995 19:06:12 -0700
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         "Sheila E. Murphy" <semurphy@INDIRECT.COM>
Subject:      Re: readings desiderata
 
Jordan, On the matter of the readings issue, Bev Carver and I have been
doing a series at the Scottsdale Center for the Arts for about nine years.
One novelty item that we include every few months (we put on monthly
programs each year from about September until May) is to select a particular
visual arts exhibition that's on display.  We select from that show several
pieces that we invite specific people to respond to (NOT INTERPRET!) with a
new text.  On the night of performance, the audience is guided from piece to
piece (sculpture, painting, etc.), at which we make a stop.  The education
director from the center staff shares some information about the visual
artist, the work; we then introduce the writer, who reads the new piece.
The audience benefits from having at least two senses working at once.  This
format tends to offer very stimulating possibilities and is consistently
popular.
 
Sheila Murphy
