Date:         Tue, 31 Oct 1995 23:41:23 -0500
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         Beth Russell <ER0595@CNSVAX.ALBANY.EDU>
Subject:      the Hypertextual possibilities
 
 I must say that in reading George P. Landow's _Hypertext: The Convergence
 of Contemporary Critical Theory and Technology_ (Johns Hopkins UP) I've
  found it fascinating on one level, and quite redundant (and not in a
 negative sense of the word, no offense to George or friends of George)
 on another level. The fascinating things about this text are:
 
1) the implications of hypertextual linkin' 'n thinkin' in terms of
say _power_ structures (he does begin his print culture text with
a quote from Foucault), the availability and the production of hieratic
(interesting sections on hieroglyphs) and hierarchical modificatiions,
 
2) the seeming _break_ within the linearity of the "text" (as we used to
term it) that hypertext (now, hypermedia) produces or enables--in terms of
some cultural conceptions of what constitutes an "author",
 
3) Landow's ideas of the convergence of say, Derridean notions of inter-
weaving/excesses (within writing) with _contemporary_ hypertextual/media
constructions...Landow believes that the hyper-world has enabled the
previous structuralist and post-structralist discourses to become better
understood (whereas before, these theories were somehow arcane systems of
mystified knowledge)...the hyper-world, that is, via modes of Web linkages,
non-linear directories, etc. seems to explain or elucidate these po/struct.
theories _naturally_...(on a monitor of course).
 
Landow quotes Walter J. Ong (_Orality and Literacy_) and I feel this
directly relates to the issues of power, who _owns_ a text, who _knows_
a text, and of course, the possibility of _challenging_ the text:
 
"The author might be challenged if only he/she could be reached, but the
author cannot be reached in any book. There is no way directly to refute
a text. After absolutely total and devestating refutation, it says exactly the
same thing as before. This is one reason why 'the book says'is popularly
tantamount to 'it is true'. It is also one reason why books have been burnt.
A text stating what the whole world knows is false will state falsehood
forever, so longas the text exists."
 
What does this mean for hypertext, virtual networks, the WWW, and more to
come...etc etc.?
 
Perhaps, the redundant aspectd of this body of lexia _Hypertext_, seem
to be the under-development of certain concepts, yet in the converse,
certain ideas are brought about repetitively. The notion of "non-linearity"
and the multiplicity of authorship, for examples, (regarding hypertextual
models) are repeated throughout the work, in almost every chapter.
When one reads these concepts over and over, it appears to be an ironic
commentary on the nature of computer replication itself (or print culture
textual reproduction), as well as a Barthes-ian idea of reproducion or
inscription. For Landow praises Barthes' _S/Z_ for Barthes' pre-cyber
understandings of "linking", "nodes", "networks", "webs" and "paths":
 
Landow cites from _S/Z_, "In this ideal text, the networks [reseaux]
are many and interact, witout any one of them being able to surpass the
rest; thistext is a galaxy of signifiers, not a structure of signifieds;
it has no beginning; it is reversible; we gain access to it by several
entrances, none of which can be authoritatively declared to be the main
one; the codes it mobilizes extend _as far as the eye can reach_, they
are indeterminable...;the systems of meaning can never take over this
absolutely plural text, but their number is never closed, based as it is
on the infinty of language".
 
Again, like the Internet? Or hypertextual mediums?
Although Landow repeats, he may just be attempting to _come at the text_
through several different angles or entranceways--thus, modeling his
text on that of the hypertext as well as Barthes' _S/Z_, I'm not entirely
sure. This dilemma might rest within an argument of form vs. function.
 
And I agree that there are differences between traditional _text_
and hypertext and Landow does talk a bit about the Hypercard program
"by opening the text-processing program [Hypercard], or editor, as it is
known, you can take notes, or you can write against my interpretations,
against my text. Although you cannot change my text, you can read the
readerly text in two ways not possible with a book.." In a sense, the
"discussion list" (computerized) is just such an example of _reading
against the text_...the idea that Landow is attmpting to put on the
virtual table.
 
 
c'est tout
 
Beth Russell
